		<description>Caliber: 9x19mm Parabellum. 34-round detachable mag. Select-Fire.
		
A blowback-operation 9mm submachine-gun used by the British military during the Cold War. Designed by George William Patchett during WWII, the Patchett or so-called "Sterling" SMG was meant to be a replacement for the ubiquitous Sten gun. It did not end up seeing major use during the war itself, but would be adopted in the 1950s (replacing the Sten as intended), and variations of it would continue to be used in British service well into the 1990s.\nThe L2A2 variant (called the Mk.III at Sterling Armament Company) was adopted in 1955 to replace the L2A1/Mk.II, with its most notable change being a modified buttstock. Less than a month after it was put into service, it was replaced by the improved L2A3/Mk.IV, the final major standard iteration on the platform.

The Mk 7 series is a set of prototype "machine pistol" variants of the SMG, with short barrels. The A4 variant has an integrated foregrip.</description>
